## ğŸ” **Deep Dive: Conditional Problem Solving**

### âœ… **1. Types of Conditional Statements**

Understanding how to *control the flow of your program*.

| Type                  | Example Syntax (C/Java-style)        | When to Use                           |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------- |
| `if`                  | `if (a > 0) { ... }`                 | One condition, do something if true   |
| `if-else`             | `if (a > 0) { ... } else { ... }`    | Two outcomes (true/false)             |
| `if - else if - else` | Chain of conditions                  | Multiple condition paths              |
| `nested if`           | `if (a > 0) { if (a < 10) { ... } }` | Inside another if â€” dependent logic   |
| `switch`              | `switch(choice) { case 1: ... }`     | Multiple options with constant values |

---

### âœ… **2. Flow Control Visualization**

```text
if (cond1)
    â””â”€â”€ do A
else if (cond2)
    â””â”€â”€ do B
else
    â””â”€â”€ do C
```

âš ï¸ Common mistake: Not using `{}` when multiple statements exist in one block.

---

### âœ… **3. Common Patterns in Conditionals**

#### ğŸ”¸ a) **Range-Based Decision**

```js
if (marks >= 90) grade = 'A';
else if (marks >= 80) grade = 'B';
...
```

#### ğŸ”¸ b) **Logical Operators**

```js
if (age >= 18 && citizen == true) {
   vote = true;
}
```

#### ğŸ”¸ c) **Nested If**

```js
if (passed) {
   if (marks >= 90) { ... }
   else { ... }
}
```

Use when **one condition depends on another**.

